[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "Overview"]
[Result "*"]

{ Hello everyone, I am an FM Amro El Jawich from Lebanon. I am a 3-time Lebanese champion and the youngest to achieve that feat at the age of 15. My current ELO is 2274 and I am currently working on getting the IM title. This is the first course I have published. I hope you like it and the others that are yet to come. }
1. e4 d6
{ In my view this is Black's most accurate move order to get to the Philidor Defence. The alternative  1...e5  is examined in Chapter 3: Different move orders. }
2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 { 3...g6  would be a Pirc Defense. } 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4
{ 5.♗c4 is the mainline, and to be honest, there is nothing wrong with it, but being a tactical player it didn't suit me too well. Also, there is a junction of variations on almost every move, so why not choose something more active and full of tricks? Certainly I can't promise you a crushing win after a pawn sacrifice in all lines; however, I can assure you that you will achieve a playable position and compensation for the sacrificed material. I actually played 5. g4!? while barely preparing it and the play seems to flow easily. I also would like to point out that GM Alexei Shirov played it very successfully in his games. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "Shirov, Alexei vs. Hoffman, Alejandro"]
[Result "*"]

{ I would like to show this game in the introduction to show how fun the pawn sacrifice 5. g4 can be. }
1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4
{ The starting position of this course. } 5... Nxg4 6. Rg1 Ngf6 7. Bc4 h6 8.
Be3 Nb6 9. Bb3 { All moves until here are present in our theory part. } 9...
Bg4 { A mistake. Black's best move is discussed in chapter 1, line 68. } 10.
dxe5 { White is already winning. } 10... Bxf3 11. Qxf3 dxe5 12. Qf5 Nbd7 13.
O-O-O c6 14. f4 { Breaking open the center, where Black's king is stuck. }
14... Qe7 15. fxe5 Nxe5 16. Bd4
{ The two Bishops are unstoppable in an open position. } 16... Nfd7 17. Bxe5
{ 17.Nb5 !  Not an easy move to spot.  cxb5  18.Bxe5  Nxe5  19.Bxf7+  Nxf7   19...Qxf7  20.Qxe5+  Be7  21.Rxg7  +-  Black's pieces are falling one by one.  20.Qxb5+  A nice killing move. }
17... Nxe5 18. Nd5 cxd5 19. Ba4+ Nd7 20. Rxd5 O-O-O 21. Bxd7+ Rxd7 22. Rgd1
Qg5+ 23. Qxg5 hxg5 24. Rxd7 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Ch.1 Accepting the sacrifice"]
[Black "1. Accepting the sacrifice: 6... exd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4 Nxg4 6. Rg1
{ After Black has accepted the sacrifice, the main idea is to develop our pieces very quickly and start attacking Black's weaknesses  (mainly f7)  . While doing this, we attack the g4-knight giving us an even further development lead. In addition, 5... Nxg4 opens the g-file for our rook to pressure g7 - making it hard for Black to complete his development. }
6... exd4
{ The downside of this move is that Black is opening the center where White will be more developed and coordinated. }
7. Nxd4 Nge5
{ Black thinks that the knight is safe here as  8.f4  can't be played in the view of  ...Qh4+.  This is true but there is another way for White  ! }
8. Bg5
{ White challenges the queen on d8 and asks Black how he is going to keep her safe. }
8... Be7 { This just gives back the pawn while White keeps the initiative. } 9.
Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nf5 Qd8 11. Nxg7+ Kf8 12. Qh5 Nf6 13. Qh6
{ The only move, but enough ! } 13... Nfg4 14. Ne6+ Ke8 15. Qg7
{ Securing our queen while attacking both Black's queen and rook. } 15... Nf3+
16. Kd1
{ Black managed to prevent White from castling but he still faces the same double threat to his queen and rook. }
16... Bxe6 17. Qxh8+ Kd7 18. Qxd8+ Rxd8 19. Rg3
{ Black has simplified the position and will grab a few pawns, but White will still be clearly better. }
19... Nfxh2 20. Bg2 Nxf2+ 21. Ke2 Nhg4 22. Rf3
{ White will play Rxf2 next with a large advantage. } *

