[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4 Nxg4 6. Rg1
{ After Black has accepted the sacrifice, the main idea is to develop our pieces very quickly and start attacking Black's weaknesses  (mainly f7)  . While doing this, we attack the g4-knight giving us an even further development lead. In addition, 5... Nxg4 opens the g-file for our rook to pressure g7 - making it hard for Black to complete his development. }
6... exd4
{ The downside of this move is that Black is opening the center where White will be more developed and coordinated. }
7. Nxd4 Nge5
{ Black thinks that the knight is safe here as  8.f4  can't be played in the view of  ...Qh4+.  This is true but there is another way for White  ! }
8. Bg5
{ White challenges the queen on d8 and asks Black how he is going to keep her safe. }
8... Nf6 9. Qe2
{ Now ...Qh4 is no longer a threat. White is ready to challenge the knight on e5 and castle long. }
9... h6 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Qh5
{ Preventing ...h5 and keeping Black's dark-squared bishop locked in. } 11...
c6 12. O-O-O { White will play f4 next. There is no need to hurry with it. }
12... Qa5
{ A tricky move. Black prepares ...Nd3+ with check to capture our Queen. } 13.
Kb1
{ Keeping our Queen on its strong square while preventing the ...Nd3 threat by moving the King. }
13... Qc5 14. f4 Ng6 15. f5
{ White should be very careful with this decision. Usually we avoid such moves as this will give back the e5-square for the knight, but here there is concrete idea behind it. }
15... Ne5 16. Rg3 { Preparing a rook shift that will be obvious later. } 16...
Bd7 17. Ne6 { Now it's clear: the f5-pawn supports the knight on e6. } 17...
Bxe6 18. fxe6 O-O-O 19. Nd5
{ Threatening the f6-pawn as well as to play e6-e7. } 19... cxd5 20. Rc3
{ The Rook is shifted exactly at the right moment. } 20... fxe6 21. Rxc5+ dxc5
22. Qh3 { It may take some time but White will convert his advantage. } *

