1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4 Nxg4 6. Rg1
{ After Black has accepted the sacrifice, the main idea is to develop our pieces very quickly and start attacking Black's weaknesses  (mainly f7)  . While doing this, we attack the g4-knight giving us an even further development lead. In addition, 5... Nxg4 opens the g-file for our rook to pressure g7 - making it hard for Black to complete his development. }
6... exd4
{ The downside of this move is that Black is opening the center where White will be more developed and coordinated. }
7. Nxd4 Ngf6 8. Qe2 c6 9. Bf4 Qc7 10. O-O-O
{ White is almost fully developed. Blacks king is stuck in the center and the d6-pawn is weak. Nf5 or Ndb5 is coming, and if Black plays ...Ne5 we can move our dark-squared bishop and break with f4-e5. Here is a sample line: }
10... Ne5
{ Black is trying to fix the center, but as we said before we can push him away. }
11. Bg5
{ Threatening to ruin Black's pawn structure and of course making space for the f2-f4 push. }
11... Be7 12. f4 Bg4 { Black tries to develop with tempo which is logical. }
13. Qg2 { The most active square for our queen. } 13... Bxd1
{ Black can go for the material but we will soon get it back. } 14. fxe5 dxe5
15. Nf5 { Saving the knight while threatening the d1-bishop and the g7-pawn. }
15... Bg4 { Black can't save his Bishop. } 16. Nxg7+ Kd8 17. Bxf6
{ Removing the defender. } 17... Bxf6 18. Qxg4 Rg8 19. Ne6+
{ Black loses a rook. } *

