[White "2. Ch.1 Accepting the sacrifice"]
[Black "15. Accepting the sacrifice: 6... exd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4 Nxg4 6. Rg1
{ After Black has accepted the sacrifice, the main idea is to develop our pieces very quickly and start attacking Black's weaknesses  (mainly f7)  . While doing this, we attack the g4-knight giving us an even further development lead. In addition, 5... Nxg4 opens the g-file for our rook to pressure g7 - making it hard for Black to complete his development. }
6... exd4
{ The downside of this move is that Black is opening the center where White will be more developed and coordinated. }
7. Nxd4 Nde5
{ Black thinks he is activating his pieces but soon they will be pushed back. }
8. h3 { The first kick. } 8... Nf6 9. f4 { The second kick. } 9... Ng6 10. Qe2
{ If Black moves his knight to g6 nothing changes. White continues developing, but we prefer putting the queen on e2 so that after a future Bg2 Black won't be able to play ...Nh4 with a fork. }
10... Bd7 11. Bd2
{ Be3  c5  followed by Qe7 and Bc6 might put some pressure on the e4-pawn }
11... Qe7
{ It's logical that Black prepares long castling, as castling kingside is just suicidal. }
12. O-O-O O-O-O 13. Bg2 Nh4 14. Bh1 Ng6 15. Nb3
{ Although the pawns in front of Blacks king are all unmoved, he is not safe. White has various attacking ideas: Na5 with e4-e5 points at the b7-pawn, the Bishop can go to e3 eyeing the a7-pawn, and the Queen can be transferred quickly via c4. }
