{ After Black has accepted the sacrifice, the main idea is to develop our pieces very quickly and start attacking Black's weaknesses  (mainly f7)  . While doing this, we attack the g4-knight giving us an even further development lead. In addition, 5... Nxg4 opens the g-file for our rook to pressure g7 - making it hard for Black to complete his development. }
6... Ngf6 7. Bc4
{ Unsurprisingly White develops while targeting Black's f7-weakness. It might look early but Black has to play very accurately if he doesn't want to lose immediately. }
7... exd4 8. Qxd4
{ Now we capture with the queen in order to speed up our development. } 8... c6
{ This is playable but it weakens the d6-pawn. } 9. Bf4
{ Developing while attacking the newly created weakness on d6. } 9... b5
{ Black uses the c6-pawn to play ...b5, but it doesn't work. } 10. Ng5
{ A sacrifice that has to work, as Black has barely developed any piece and wasted a lot of time with pawn moves. }
10... bxc4 11. Qxc4 { A double attack on f7 and c6. } 11... Qe7 12. Qxc6 h6 13.
Nb5 { Again d6 and c7 are easy targets for our knight. } 13... hxg5 14. Nxd6+
Kd8 15. Rxg5
{ Counting the material we are only down a piece while Black is still in trouble. I'll show a few possible continuations to prove White has full compensation. }
15... Qe6 16. Nxf7+ Ke7 17. Nd6 Nxe4 18. O-O-O
{ White brings his king to safety and continues to put pressure on Black. }
18... Nxg5 { Black wins a rook at the cost of being mated. } 19. Bxg5+ Nf6 20.
Qe8# *

