[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4 Nxg4 6. Rg1
{ After Black has accepted the sacrifice, the main idea is to develop our pieces very quickly and start attacking Black's weaknesses  (mainly f7)  . While doing this, we attack the g4-knight giving us an even further development lead. In addition, 5... Nxg4 opens the g-file for our rook to pressure g7 - making it hard for Black to complete his development. }
6... Ngf6 7. Bc4
{ Unsurprisingly White develops while targeting Black's f7-weakness. It might look early but Black has to play very accurately if he doesn't want to lose immediately. }
7... h6
{ This seems the best move, covering the g5-square to prevent Ng5 which would attack f7. However, Black is losing precious time. }
8. Be3 c6 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Qd3 Qc7
{ This natural move is refuted effectively. } 11. Bxf7+ Kxf7 12. Qc4+
{ Black has the choice between two losing king moves. } 12... Ke8
{ This allows White's queen fatal entry. } 13. Qe6+ Be7 14. Rxg7 Qd6 15. Qf7+
Kd8 16. Rd1 Rf8 17. Qb3
{ Retreating for now but the queen will return to e6 when Black moves his queen. }
17... Nd5 18. Rg3
{ The only but good enough ! White protects his f3-knight while Black's d5-knight is lost. }
