{ Sacrificing a piece for the sake of opening lines and diagonals toward Black's king who is stuck in the center. As you will see later Black has to play several only moves to stay in the game. }
15... bxc4 16. Nxf6+ Nxf6 17. Bxc4 Bxc4 18. Qxc4 Rd8 19. Qc6+ Nd7 20. Kb1 Qb4
{ The only move and a hard one to find. } 21. Rd3 Qe7 { Another only move. }
22. Bxa7 Qe6 23. Qb5
{ Of course refusing to exchange queens in order to keep the pressure. } 23...
h5 { Trying to activate the h8-rook. } 24. Be3 { Not allowed ! } 24... Rb8
{ These kind of positions I hate to play as Black because they are so hard to defend. }
25. Qa4 Rb4 26. Qa7 Nb8 27. Qc7
{ Again we are going too deep but I will continue for the sake of the readers. }
27... Nc6 28. Rgd1 Rb8 29. Rd6 Bxd6 30. Rxd6 Qc4 31. Qd7+ Kf8 32. Rxc6 Qf1+ 33.
Bc1 Kg8 34. Rc8+ Rxc8 35. Qxc8+ Kh7 36. Qf5+ Kg8 37. Qxe5
{ After so many only moves for Black, we reach a position where only White can play for the win. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Ch.1 Accepting the sacrifice"]
[Black "99. Accepting the sacrifice: 6... Ngf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4 Nxg4 6. Rg1
{ After Black has accepted the sacrifice, the main idea is to develop our pieces very quickly and start attacking Black's weaknesses  (mainly f7)  . While doing this, we attack the g4-knight giving us an even further development lead. In addition, 5... Nxg4 opens the g-file for our rook to pressure g7 - making it hard for Black to complete his development. }
6... Ngf6 7. Bc4
{ Unsurprisingly White develops while targeting Black's f7-weakness. It might look early but Black has to play very accurately if he doesn't want to lose immediately. }
7... h6
{ This seems the best move, covering the g5-square to prevent Ng5 which would attack f7. However, Black is losing precious time. }
8. Be3 c6 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Qd3 b5 11. Bb3 Qa5 12. O-O-O Ba6
{ Threatening ...b4. } 13. Nd2
{ From this position a few games have been played but there are many interesting positions which can be reached from here. }
13... O-O-O 14. Bxf7
{ Black gives back his extra pawn for the sake of the safety of his king. You can check the games section. }
14... Nc5 15. Qf1 b4 16. Ne2 Kb8 17. f3
{ Now we reach a materially equal position with a lot of play for both sides. Here is an example of how play may continue. }
17... Rd7 18. Bb3 Bd6 19. Kb1 Nxb3 20. axb3 Rhd8 21. Nc4 Bxc4 22. bxc4 Bc5 23.
Rxd7 Nxd7 24. Qf2 Qb6 25. Bxc5 Nxc5 26. Nc1 *

