[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4
{ Let's check what happens if Black refuses to take the pawn. For me it's enough that the position will be tactically complex with equal material but of course I need to show something. }
5... g6 6. g5
{ Pushing Blacks knight to an uncomfortable square on the edge of the board while gaining space. }
6... Nh5
{ The computer gives an edge for White here and suggests many times to exchange on e5. I prefer to keep the tension and play as suggested, because most of the time the engine changes its mind in the end. }
7. Be3 Bg7 8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O c6 10. Be2
{ We reach a position with opposite-side castling with a lot of possibilities. Play may continue as follows: }
10... Qe7 11. Rhg1 Nb6 12. Nh4
{ Threatening Bxh5 or Nf5 opening the kingside. Black is forced to react as fast as possible in the center. }
12... exd4 13. Bxd4 Bxd4 14. Qxd4 Nf4
{ Black was able to activate his h5-knight at the cost of his dark-squared bishop, leaving him with weak dark squares. }
15. Bf1 d5 16. Qe3 Qe5 17. Ng2 { Getting the knight back into play. } 17... Nh3
{ If Black refuses to exchange, we have a nice way to keep the knight out of play. }
18. f4
{ A nice intermediate move protecting the g5-pawn and removing Black's queen from her active square. }
18... Qg7 19. Rh1
{ Again Black's knight is causing him problems and will be in danger after our g2-knight moves. }
*

