1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4
{ Let's check what happens if Black refuses to take the pawn. For me it's enough that the position will be tactically complex with equal material but of course I need to show something. }
5... exd4 { Black can try opening the center. } 6. Nxd4 h6
{ The only real try after Black has opened the center. } 7. Bg2
{ Now that Black has opened the center and prevented g5, we can simply develop and enjoy our space advantage. }
7... g6
{ Black wishes to develop his bishop to g7, but he lost a lot of time. } 8. h3
Bg7 9. Be3 O-O 10. Qd2
{ White has obvious pressure on Black's king. Play may continue as follows: }
10... Nb6 11. Bxh6 Nc4 12. Qc1
{ Black can regain his pawn but with a very weak king. } 12... Bxh6 13. Qxh6
Nxb2 14. Rb1
{ Although White's play is on the kingside, there is this amazing idea that requires White to first force Black's knight to c4. }
14... Nc4 15. Nf5
{ Since the g-pawn is the only real defender of Black's king, White should immediately challenge it. }
15... gxf5 16. gxf5 Nh7 17. Bf1
{ Now the idea is clear: White forced the knight to c4 so that Bf1 comes with a double threat ! Rg1 and Bxc4 are two big threats. }
17... Qf6 { Of course Black has to defend against the mate threat. } 18. Qxf6
Nxf6 19. Rg1+ Kh8 20. Bxc4
{ White enjoys an extra pawn and a much safer king. } *

