1. e4 e5
{ 1...d6  is the best way for Black if he wishes to play the Philidor Defence. }
2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 Nd7 4. Bc4 c6
{ Preventing White from occupying the d5-square with his Queen  (after the exchange on e5)  so that ...Be7 becomes possible. }
5. O-O Ngf6
{ The only defence against the white threat of Ng5 was ...Nh6, but after ...Ngf6 this is not possible any longer. }
6. dxe5
{ Don't hurry with Ng5 as Black can still defend with ...d6-d5. After exchanging on e5, this is no longer possible. }
6... Nxe5 7. Nxe5 dxe5 8. Bxf7+
{ Black's king is overloaded, having to protect both the Queen on d8 and the pawn on f7. }
8... Ke7 { The only move for Black that doesnt lose his Queen. } 9. Bb3 Qxd1
10. Rxd1 a5 { Threatening to trap White's bishop with ...a4 and ...b5. } 11. a4
{ Preventing Black's idea. } 11... Nxe4 12. f3
{ Although Black regains his missing pawn, he will still suffer from his lack of development and misplaced king. }
12... Nc5
{ If Black doesn't realize the importance of closing the d-file for our rook or the h4-d8 diagonal for our bishop then mate will folllow ! }
13. Bg5+ Ke8 14. Rd8# *

