1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 Nd7 4. Bc4 c6 5. O-O Be7 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Ng5 Bxg5 8.
Qh5 Qe7 9. Qxg5 Qxg5 10. Bxg5 { I was prepared until this move. } 10... h6 11.
Be3 Ngf6 12. f3
{ Sooner or later I have to play this move, so I didn't commit my knight to a particular square yet. }
12... O-O
{ 12...b5  13.Bd3  Now Black's queenside is vulnerable and a2-a4 will put strong pressure on his position. }
13. a4
{ Black has no active plan and White will increase the pressure slowly. } 13...
Ne8 14. Rd1 Nc7 15. Nc3
{ 15.Bf1  was better, waiting to see how Black will continue before commiting the knight. }
15... Nb6 16. Be2 Be6 17. a5
{ We have seen in the theory section many positions in which White has the advantage of the bishop pair. It's important in such positions to use the strength of the bishop's diagonal to cramp the opponent pieces and create weaknesses. }
17... Nd7 18. Rd6 Ne8 19. Rd2 Nef6 20. Rad1 Rfc8 21. Na4 Kf8 22. Nc5 Nxc5 23.
Bxc5+ Ke8 24. Bd6 Nd7 25. g3
{ when you have two bishops, it's important to provoke weaknesses on both sides of the board. }
25... f6 26. f4 g6 27. Ba3 Nf8 28. fxe5 { 28.Rd6 ! } 28... fxe5 29. Rf1 c5 30.
Bb5+ Ke7 31. b4 b6 32. bxc5 bxc5 33. Bb2
{ Although we both have three isolated pawns, only Black's pawns can be attacked. }
33... Bh3 34. Rff2 Rab8 35. c4 a6
{ Dont ask me why he played this, but Black's position is hopeless anyway. }
36. Bxa6 Rd8 37. Bb5 Ke6 38. Rd5 Nd7 39. a6 g5 40. Bc3
{ 40.Bxd7+ !  Rxd7  41.Rxe5+  Kd6  42.Rf6+  Kc7  43.Rxc5+  Kd8  44.Rf8+  Ke7  45.Rxb8  would have decided the game immediately. }
40... Nf6 41. Rxe5+ Kf7 42. Rd5 Rxd5 43. Rxf6+ Ke7 44. exd5 *

